comment_data.body:
> I think the best approach here would be to use `nvim_ui_attach()` (or `vim.ui.attach` from Lua) to hook into `ext_cmdline` so you can have a (floating window) buffer as the actual commandline. Obviously, this would require adding support for that.

Would we not rather keep this in C? ext_cmdline seems kind of roundabout when internally we can just open a floating window and set the cmdline text in a buffer. I made a quick mock-up that works quite well already. Not much more than the following is required:

```c
// Init in command_line_enter()
FloatConfig fconfig = FLOAT_CONFIG_INIT;
fconfig.height = 1;
fconfig.width = Columns;
fconfig.row = Rows;
fconfig.zindex = kZIndexCmdlinePopupMenu;
fconfig.style = kWinStyleMinimal;
cmdline_win = win_new_float(NULL, false, fconfig, NULL);
cmdline_buf = buflist_new(NULL, NULL, 1, BLN_NOOPT | BLN_DUMMY);
win_enter(cmdline_win, true);
set_curbuf(cmdline_buf, DOBUF_SPLIT);
set_option_value(kOptFiletype, STATIC_CSTR_AS_OPTVAL("vim"), OPT_LOCAL);
set_option_value(kOptWinhighlight, STATIC_CSTR_AS_OPTVAL("NormalFloat:Normal"), OPT_LOCAL);

...

// Replacement redrawcmd()
char buf[MAXPATHL];
buf[0] = (char)ccline.cmdfirstc;
xstrlcpy(buf + 1, ccline.cmdbuff, MAXPATHL);
ml_replace_buf(cmdline_buf, 1, buf, true);
changed_lines(cmdline_buf, 1, 0, 1, 0, false);
ccline.cmdspos = cmd_screencol(ccline.cmdpos);
cmdline_win->w_cursor.col = ccline.cmdspos;
update_screen();
```

Obviously a lot of dead code would need to be removed and probably edge cases considered.
